  "summary": "For twenty-five years, I&rsquo;ve shared ideas with artists who write code. The internet is essential for us; it&rsquo;s not just for documentation, but the primary place where our work is shared, discussed, and exhibited. Social Codes is a view into this community of hybrid artists/coders in 2021.\n\nThis is an exhibition of software art, also called generative art. All of the work is comprised of code written by artists to create visual experiences. While some works relate to the visual histories of drawing, painting, and animation, all are native digital art&mdash;a performance of code choreographed by the artist. Since the 1960s, code has evolved from languages written by engineers for room-sized computers to artist-created languages running in browsers. Each programming language is a different material.\n\nIn September 2020, I began researching generative art on social media, asking on Twitter: &ldquo;Who&rsquo;s doing the most interesting work in this space?&rdquo; This resulted in a <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1bSg5QzNrVtRUjYUSQQ4r6L25xrgUZevGdFMnuwCmMFc/edit?usp=sharing\" target=\"_blank\">public document</a> with a crowdsourced list of over three hundred people&mdash;the seed for this exhibition.\n\nIn Social Codes, these works are presented together intentionally instead of spread across various platforms. The majority of the work relates to the coding platform Processing and the JavaScript library p5.js. As a co-founder of Processing, I am tuned into that community, so while this selection doesn&rsquo;t represent everything happening online, it is an invitation to seek out more. There are decades of amazing works to explore through your browser.",
  "coverImage": "https://imagedelivery.net/iCRs13uicXIPOWrnuHbaKA/828f2aa7-7edd-4961-f5c7-0fbac8a9ec00/raw"
